STP - SPANNING TREE PROTOCOL
============================

🌐 STP (Spanning Tree Protocol) is a Layer 2 protocol used in switching to prevent looping issues in networks with redundant paths. 
Without STP, switches could forward frames endlessly in a loop, causing broadcast storms, MAC table instability, and multiple frame copies reaching devices—basically, network chaos.



PROBLEMS WITH REDUNANT NETWORKS
1. BROADCAST STORM
2. INFINITE FRAMES TRANSMITTED & RECEIVED
3. MAC ADDRESS TABLE INSTABILITY

HOW STP WORKS
1. STP IS TURNED ON BY DEFAULT
	3 VARIATION OF LIGHT
	- OFF
	- AMBER - NOT YET CONNECTED TO NETWORK, TIME WERE STP IS INITILIAZING
	- GREEN - STP PROCESS IS DONE AND IS IN FORWARDING STATE
2. HOW SWITCHED DETECT IF THERE ARE SWITCHING LOOPS ?
	A. EACH SWITCH HAS ITS OWN BRIDGE ID
		BRIDGE ID	- BRIDGE PRIORITY 32768 - DEFAULT VALUE
				- SYSTME ID - MAC ADDRESS
	B.SWITCHES SENDS OUT BPDUs OUT ON ALL ACTIVE INTERFACES 
		BPDU 	- BRIDGE PROTOCOL DATA UNIT
			- CONTENTS: ROOT BRIDGE ID, 
					SENDERS BRIDGE ID 
					STP PORT COST FROM SENDER TO THE ROOT BRIDGE
					STP TIMERS
3. HOW DO SWITCHES KNOW WHICH LINK/INTERFACES TO BLOCK TO PREVENT SWITCHING LOOP?
	A. OPERATING STATES:
		1. FORWARDING STATES
			- GREEN LED LIGHT
			- NORMAL OPERATION
			- TRANSMITS AND RECEIVES FRAMES
			- TRANSMITS AND RECEIVES BPDUs
		2. BLOCKING STATES
			- AMBER LED LIGHT
			- DROPS FRAMES RECEIVED
			- DOES NOT SEND OUT FRAMES
			- DOES NOT SEND OUT BPDUS
			- RECEIVES BPDUS 

	B. TRANSITIONAL STATES
		
		1. LISTENING
			- DOES NOT TRANSMIT BPDU, BUT RECEIVES BPDU
			- DISCARD MAC ADD LEARNED FROM THIS INTERFACE
		2. LEARNING
			- DOES NOT TRANSMIT BPDU, BUT RECEIVED BPDU
			- DOES NOT TRANSMIT FRAMES, BUT RECEIVES FRAMES
			- POPULATES MAC ADD LEARNED ON THIS INTERFACE
		3. DISABLED



4. STP PROCESS:
	STEP 1. THEY NEED TO ELECT A ROOT BRIDGE [RB]
			- CHECKING CRITERIA FOR JUDGING TO ELECT RB: LOWEST VALUE
				1. LOWEST BRIDGE
				2. MAC ADDRESS / SYSTEM ID
			- NOTE: AT THE START OF ELECTION, ALL SWITCHES CLAIM TO BE THE ROOT BRIDGE
			- BASED ON BPDU CONTENT, THEY ELECT THEIR RB
			- DEFAULT STP COSTS
				10 MBPS	100
				100 MBPS	19
				2 GBPS 	6
				10 GBPS	2
			- COST = INCOMING COST + STP PORT COST OF THE INGRESS PORT
			
			ROOT BRIDGE
			===========
			- STP FORWARDING TRAFFIC BOSS
			- CENTRAL POINT OF THE NETWORK
			- ALL POWERFUL SWITCH 
			- ALL PORTS ARE DESIGNATED PORT OR FORWARDING PORT
	
	STEP 2. THEY NEED TO ASSIGN STP PORT ROLES
			- ROOT PORT - [RP] PORT WITH LOWEST STP PORT COST GOING TO THE BRIDGE - PORT NEAR THE ROOT BRIDGE
				ALL PORTS ARE DESIGNATED PORT OR FORWARDING PORT
			- DESIGNATED PORT - [DP] A FORWARDING PORT. STP COMBO  [RP-DP], [BP-DP] - ONE DP PER LINK ONLY
												 ----------------
			- FIND THE ROOT PORT ON ALL NON-ROOT BRIDGE SWITCHES
			- ALTERNATE BLOCKING PORT [BP] - DROP FRAMES
			
	STEP 3. THEN, THEN CAN BLOCK AN INTERFACE - ALL LINKS W/O A ROOT PORT [RP] WILL BECOME THE BLOCKING PORT 
			- BLOCKING PORT IS THE ONE WITH HIGHEST MAC ADDRESS
			- ALL LINK WITHOUT A ROOT PORT, ONE PORT MUST BE BLOCKING
			- PORT WITH HIGHER BRIDGE ID WILL BE THE BLOCKING PORT 




5. WHAT HAPPENED WHEN ONE OF THE LINK FAILED
	A. IF IT STOPS RECEIVING BPDUs ON AN INTERFACE
	B. IF IT RECEIVES A BPDU WITH A DIFFERENT VALUE

