does root port forward bpdu in a designated port in the same switch? 

No, the root port does not forward BPDUs to a designated port on the same switch. Here's how it works:

Root Port: This is the port on the switch with the best path to the root bridge. The root port receives BPDUs from the upstream switch (the one closer to the root bridge).

Designated Port: This is the port on the switch that forwards BPDUs downstream (toward switches further away from the root bridge) to ensure that the network segment remains connected to the root bridge.

BPDU Forwarding Behavior:
BPDUs received on the root port are not forwarded to the switch's own designated ports. Instead, the switch processes those BPDUs and then generates new BPDUs based on its current role and status, which it transmits out of its designated ports.
The designated ports on the switch generate and transmit their own BPDUs downstream, based on the information received from the root port or other upstream BPDUs.
Important Points:
BPDUs flow from the root bridge downward through the network.
Each switch evaluates the BPDUs it receives, recalculates its role in the spanning tree, and then sends out its own BPDUs through its designated ports.
BPDUs do not travel from the root port to other ports on the same switch; instead, the switch sends new BPDUs out its designated ports.
